      "text": " Conversely, if  $\\ell = 1$  then it's clear that Equation (4) has a nontrivial solution  $(x, y, z)$  with  $xyz = 0$ . Suppose that  $\\ell = 2$ , then  $\\mathbb{F}_q^{\\times}/L = \\{L, gL\\}$ . If  $-1 \\notin L$ , then  $-L = gL$ . In this case,  $g = -a^2 \\in L$  for some  $a \\in \\mathbb{F}_q^{\\times}$ . Then, we clearly have solutions  $(x, y, z) = (1, a, 0)$  and  $(0,1,a)$ . Suppose  $-1 \\in L$ , then  $-g^2 = b^2 \\in L$  for some  $b \\in \\mathbb{F}_q^{\\times}$  and we have the solution  $(x, y, z) = (1, 0, b)$  in this case.",
